newsitem.title: USA: INSIGHT--Charts point to rally in CBOT soybeans.
newsitem.headline: INSIGHT--Charts point to rally in CBOT soybeans.

text.p: Wednesday's rally in Chicago Board of Trade soybeans marked a key technical reversal in the January contract and charts suggested prices could climb above $7.14 a bushel in the next few weeks, market sources said.

"We do in fact, have what appears to be a breakout here which would imply a minimum move to $7.14 and a further move to $7.28 or $7.30 in the January," said Jack Scoville, analyst with Price Futures Group, a division of LIT Futures.
Support was pegged at $7.00 per bushel with initial resistance at $7.19, Scoville added.
The January contract on Wednesday settled up 11-1/2 cents per bushel at $7.07, the highest close since October 11.

"I think the harvest low is being formed right now," said Hans Kashyap, president of Analytics Research Corporation in Bethesda, Md. "Odds are (the January) is likely to head up into the $7.20 to $7.30 level."
He said the market will likely retest the lows near $6.80 or $6.90 but added "the next swing up past $7.25 or so would signal a pretty large (upward) move over the next few months."
Floor traders noted active buying interest Wednesday when the January contract first moved above $7.00 per bushel at about 1153 CST. The January peaked briefly at $7.08 before settling at $7.07.

"It was an outside day, up and good," said a floor trader who declined to be named. "It was higher than yesterday's high and lower than yesterday's low and it closed higher which could mean a key move to the upside.
"But it has to be followed by two more days up. On a technical basis, this was a big indicator," he added.
Kashyap noted charts had indicated trading Wednesday would be on the down side and could retest Monday's lows of $6.92-1/2 per bushel.
"On a very short-term basis, the fact that we did not break under the low of November 18 is very significant," Kashyap said.
On the fundemental side, Scoville said strong export and domestic demand for U.S. soybeans was supportive and prompted much of the buying interest on Monday.
"I think there is room for this market to move higher," he said. "Certainly the market appears to have turned a corner."
